2388,IssuesEvent,2016-01-08 06:35:31+00:00,5934517,dpkp/kafka-python,843444,dpkp,,,closed,Null payload for Kafka log compaction deletion feature,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dpkp/kafka-python/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/dpkp/kafka-python/labels/producer', 'name': 'producer', 'color': 'fef2c0'}]",[],2,"According to [the official doc](https://cwiki.apache.org/confluence/display/KAFKA/Log+Compaction) Kafka log compaction could be used to delete messages from the log:
```Compaction also allows from deletes. A message with a key and a null payload will be treated as a delete from the log. This delete marker will cause any prior message with that key to be removed (as would any new message with that key), but delete markers are special in they will themselves be cleaned out of the log after a period of time.```

But now there's a [limitation](https://github.com/mumrah/kafka-python/blob/master/kafka/producer/base.py#L358) in the code that doesn't allow to pass null payloads, so the deletion feature doesn't work at all. Was it done by purpose for some reasons or I can prepare a short PR to fix it?
",{},{}
2393,IssuesEvent,2017-10-05 05:00:14+00:00,5934517,dpkp/kafka-python,483314,jeffwidman,,,opened,"Produced messages with acks=1, no errors in logs, yet messages didn't appear in Kafka",[],[],0,"At my day job, we have a service that has a `KafkaProducer` instance that sends low message volume (a few thousand a week) to a Kafka topic, but all messages are quite valuable and must be received.

The producer is configured with `acks=1`, the topic has 3 replicas, with `min.isr=2`. The cluster is currently on kafka version 0.10.0.

Since it's a low-volume, high-value producer, the service explicitly logs when it produces a message, and it forces the messages to be sent to the broker by calling `producer.flush()` immediately after `producer.send()`. I am still doublechecking with the service owner, but IIRC, the service immediately checks the result of the message `future` to make sure the `future` has completed and there were no errors reported. If there are any errors, the service logs them. So because we're using `acks=1`, we know that for the service to report that a message was produced with no errors, that the message should be present on the broker.

However, twice now in production we've had problems that we traced back to the message not being in the kafka topic. The service logs say the message was successfully produced with no reported errors, yet when we use a console consumer to consume everything in the topic, these messages are not present. The service has been running for weeks, so this isn't an issue tied to producer startup/shutdown. And the Kafka cluster has been stable, with no unclean leader elections.

This issue is mostly a placeholder for me, as I intend to dig into this more deeply but haven't had time yet. But I also wanted to doublecheck with @dpkp / @tvoinarovskyi that there are no valid scenarios where this behavior is expected. 

My hunch at this point is that the messages were lost due to network issues and there's a bug somewhere in kafka-python related to the acks=1. Since the network issues are so rare, any bug like that would only rarely be encountered, and for most of our other topics the message volume is so high that if we lost a few messages we probably wouldn't realize it. So my first steps will be simulating some network failures and seeing what happens.",{},{}
2407,IssuesEvent,2017-06-01 11:52:15+00:00,5934517,dpkp/kafka-python,1180929,demestav,,,closed,poll() does not always return messages,[],[],6,"After subscribing to a partition of a topic which contains messages and then calling `poll()`, sometimes it doesn't return the messages. Even though the position can be set at an arbitrary position (using `seek()`), the `poll()` command needs to be executed multiple times to return the messages.

Example code:

	from kafka import KafkaConsumer
	from kafka import TopicPartition

	consumer = KafkaConsumer(group_id='test', bootstrap_servers='kafka')
	tp = TopicPartition('test',0)

	consumer.assign([tp])
	consumer.seek_to_beginning()
	consumer.position(tp) # Returns 0
	consumer.poll() # Returns {} --- Expecting to return the messages
	consumer.position(tp) # Returns 0 

	# Code below may need multiple runs to return the messages
	consumer.poll() # Returns the messages
	consumer.position(tp) # Returns 60
    

",{},{}
