2745,IssuesEvent,2015-09-25 23:55:34+00:00,5598737,BurntSushi/nflgame,6109991,Exnihilation,,,opened,Finding the home and away scores at the time of a given play,[],[],0,"So if I know of a particular play in a particular game, I can find that play so long as I know the playid play and eid for the game. 

For example: Antonio Brown made an excellent catch last week and I want to know more about the play, like what quarter it was, how much time was left on the clock, what down it was, etc. If I know that the `eid = ""2015092009""` and `playid = ""1553""` I can use the following function to return the correct play object:
```python
def find_play(eid, playid):
    game = nflgame.game.Game(eid)
    for drive in game.drives:
        for play in drive.plays:
            if play.playid == playid:
                return play
```
For my purposes the returned play object has all of the relevant data I could possibly want for any given play EXCEPT the current scores of the home team and away team. With that being said, is there an easy way to look up the scores at the time of a particular play? If there is no ""easy"" way, is there a way I could modify my `find_play` function to determine the scores as it iterates through the drive and play objects?

Thanks and I apologize ahead of time if I am missing something really obvious.",{},{}
2762,IssuesEvent,2015-06-30 15:05:34+00:00,1938370,Mottie/tablesorter,136959,Mottie,,,closed,"Scroller Widget - Line doesn't line up with Internet Explorer 9, 10, 11","[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Mottie/tablesorter/labels/Next%20Update', 'name': 'Next Update', 'color': 'eb6420'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Mottie/tablesorter/labels/Widget', 'name': 'Widget', 'color': '207de5'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/Mottie/tablesorter/labels/Widget-Scroller', 'name': 'Widget-Scroller', 'color': '207de5'}]",[],6,"When we use colspan in table body like this :

```
<tbody class=""tablesorter-infoOnly"">
    <tr>
        <td colspan=""2"">COLSPAN</td>
        <!-- add extra hidden td because the fixed column set to 2
             will hide 2 cells; this hidden cell is a placeholder -->
        <td style=""display: none""></td>
        <!-- this cell will show up on the right -->
        <td colspan=""8"">&nbsp;</td>
    </tr>
</tbody>
```

Line doesn't line up with Internet Explorer but works good with other browser.

You can see a demo here : http://jsfiddle.net/1a5yu8yq/42/

![capture](https://cloud.githubusercontent.com/assets/3995851/7947521/f436ab8e-097d-11e5-863c-6ccdbbbf9e8e.png)

