5802,IssuesEvent,2018-02-25 20:38:58+00:00,12420595,CamDavidsonPilon/lifelines,1027979,erikbern,,,opened,Predicting conversion rates,[],[],0,"Hi – this might be out of the scope of this library, but I've been working a bit on predicting conversion rates in the case where there is huge time lag. Turns out fitting a Weibull (or in some cases Gamma) distribution works quite well. However there's a crucial departure from survival analysis – modeling survival implies that ""everyone dies in the long run"" (the long-run conversion rate converges to 1.0) whereas when modeling conversion rates, it converges to some value 0 <= c <= 1. So there's one more parameter that I'm trying to fit for each cohort.

I've built a bunch of these models in Tensorflow but feels like I'm essentially reimplementing lifelines slowly. Wanted to see if it would make sense to do this inside lifelines or not.

Code: https://github.com/better/convoys/blob/master/convoys/regression.py (this is highly janky – it's the first time I've used Tensorflow and there's a lot of code duplication)",{},{}
