9169,IssuesEvent,2016-06-21 21:19:37+00:00,16366081,numenta/nupic.core,364113,mrcslws,1039191,numenta,opened,Synapse cleanup: Adding 4 synapses might immediately destroy 3 of them,[],[],0,"I've talked about this before, but not in a Github issue.

`Connections::createSynapse` makes room for an extra synapse, and then creates the synapse: https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/d2bc9de05be948bf699e00964c8d6c01ad64af14/src/nupic/algorithms/Connections.cpp#L126

The problem with this approach is that `createSynapse` is generally called multiple times: https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/d2bc9de05be948bf699e00964c8d6c01ad64af14/src/nupic/algorithms/TemporalMemory.cpp#L445

Depending on the initial synapse permanence, every `createSynapse` might immediately destroy the newly created synapse. So every iteration of the loop gets overwritten by the next iteration.

Instead, synapses should be cleaned up in a group, like they are in the old TP / cells4: https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/66ef718f99e860db8969646520ef2d35e3e48dc2/src/nupic/algorithms/Segment.cpp#L346",{},{}
9176,IssuesEvent,2016-10-10 12:06:44+00:00,16366081,numenta/nupic.core,15566,rhyolight,1039191,numenta,opened,Remove software version from iterative artifact file names,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic.core/labels/bounty', 'name': 'bounty', 'color': '129e5e'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic.core/labels/triage', 'name': 'triage', 'color': 'AAAAAA'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic.core/labels/type:build', 'name': 'type:build', 'color': '006b75'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic.core/labels/type:cleanup', 'name': 'type:cleanup', 'color': '006b75'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/numenta/nupic.core/labels/windows', 'name': 'windows', 'color': '5319e7'}]",[],0,"Iterative artifacts have been stored on S3 with the software version in the name of the file. This means any system that wants to fetch an artifact for a SHA not only needs to know the SHA, but also the version of the software, which is redundant and requires inspecting the source
tree to find. ",{},{}
9180,IssuesEvent,2015-12-17 00:19:45+00:00,16366081,numenta/nupic.core,239726,scottpurdy,1039191,numenta,closed,Remove Tester class from tests in test/unit/engine,[],[],0,Subtask of #208 ,{},{}
9182,IssuesEvent,2016-12-19 22:37:05+00:00,16366081,numenta/nupic.core,364113,mrcslws,1039191,numenta,closed,"SparseMatrix ""setRandomZerosOnOuter"" should take a list of counts",[],[],0,"Currently `setRandomZerosOnOuter` takes a single ""numNewNonZerosPerRow"". This is sometimes useful, but sometimes we want to set a different number on a row-by-row basis. Originally I wrote `increaseRowNonZeroCountsOnOuterTo` fills this role, but this doesn't work if you have notions of ""active cells"" and ""winner cells"" and you want to decide how many synapses to grow by looking at the active cells, but you only want to grow synapses to the winner cells.

Solution: the caller should calculate the number of synapses to grow per row, and then the caller should pass these numbers in. In other words, `setRandomZerosOnOuter` should have a second overload which takes a list of `numNewNonZerosPerRow`s.",{},{}
9188,IssuesEvent,2015-10-29 20:31:42+00:00,16366081,numenta/nupic.core,239726,scottpurdy,1039191,numenta,closed,Handle RNG seeds consistently,[],[],10,"Currently some algorithms default to `seed=-1`, which will use a random seed each time, while others default to a fixed seed. We should handle this consistently.

This issue can track everyone's opinion on it. @subutai @chetan51 @breznak 

Some current fixed seed defaults:

- [SpatialPooler](https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/c2f6d31f418b1a6b96bd11bb406f2caf9fa3be2b/src/nupic/algorithms/SpatialPooler.hpp#L87) (C++)
- [TemporalMemory](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/67b9ace8bf579b9c8b8873a9770e161f18dfd511/src/nupic/research/temporal_memory.py#L54) (Python)
- [TP](https://github.com/numenta/nupic/blob/67b9ace8bf579b9c8b8873a9770e161f18dfd511/src/nupic/research/TP.py#L80)

Some current random seed defaults:

- [Cells4.hpp](https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/c2f6d31f418b1a6b96bd11bb406f2caf9fa3be2b/src/nupic/algorithms/Cells4.hpp) (C++)
- [SVM](https://github.com/numenta/nupic.core/blob/c2f6d31f418b1a6b96bd11bb406f2caf9fa3be2b/src/nupic/algorithms/Svm.hpp#L908) (C++)",{},{}
9197,IssuesEvent,2015-05-26 16:09:24+00:00,6679704,studioimaginaire/phue,10499802,TomMcBride,1060818,studioimaginaire,opened,I'm having difficulties when the ip address of the Hue hub changes,[],[],0,"I'm using both Windows 7 and a Raspberry Pi to control lights. I do testing and coding in Python mostly on Windows but the RPi does most of the controlling since I leave it on all the time. Everything works fine until I have a power outage (or, equivalently, disconnect and reconnect power to my router). I have a number of devices on my home network: 3 computers, a couple of printers, TiVo, etc. The Hue hub always seems to get a different ip address when this happens. This means that my programs no longer can connect to the hub. I can figure out what the new ip address is when this happens and change the programs but that's not enough. I find that I have to go through the press-the-button-on-the-hub process again for each system. Is there some way to avoid that?

I notice that I don't have to do anything like that on my iPad -- it doesn't seem to be bothered by the ip change. This problem doesn't happen often and the RPi sends me email to let me know about the problem. My difficulty is that I'm not always at home and there is no way to push the button remotely. Any ideas or suggestions would be welcome.",{},{}
