11501,IssuesEvent,2015-01-20 20:33:31+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,7378,baroquebobcat,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,.BUILD.pyc files are not cleaned by clean-all ,[],[],0,"Since pants caches BUILD files bytecode files along side their BUILD files, clean-all does not update them. This can cause strange behavior that can only be resolved by using `git clean -fdx`.

The assumption https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/master/src/python/pants/base/build_file.py#L235-L236 makes is that if a cache is younger or the same age as the file it caches, then the cached bytecode should be used. If that assumption is ever wrong, it can be really confusing.",{},{}
11503,IssuesEvent,2016-07-14 00:19:34+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,46740,stuhood,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,Clarify split and rename one/both of pants-ignore and ignore-patterns,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/engine', 'name': 'engine', 'color': 'fbca04'}]",[],0,"`--pants-ignore` is implemented by ProjectTree, and should be used when pants should always ignore a file.

`--ignore-pattern` is implemented by the BuildFileMapper, and is used when pants should only ignore a pattern while searching for BUILD files.

The names and helf of these options don't make this obvious, but they should.

(ProjectTree is not yet used everywhere for filesystem consumption: most importantly, it is not used by twitter.commons, so it does not apply to the current implementation of globs. Once we've switched to the new engine, it will be used to execute globs as well.)",{},{}
11509,IssuesEvent,2017-01-27 06:23:09+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,46740,stuhood,3065172,pantsbuild,closed,Switch from `&Vec<T>` to `&[T]` in function parameters,"[{'id': 268094252, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/engine', 'name': 'engine', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}, {'id': 472006774, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/pantsbuild/pants/labels/native', 'name': 'native', 'color': 'fef2c0', 'default': False}]",[],1,"...particularly for `invoke_runnable`.

The former (`Vec`) is guaranteed to be on the heap, but the latter (`slice`) can reference either something on the heap or on the stack, which allows for more calling flexibility.

For example:
```
// requires allocation
let args = vec![1, 2, 3];
my_func(&args);
```

```
// does not require allocation
let args = [1, 2, 3];
my_func(&args);
```",{},{}
11516,IssuesEvent,2018-06-18 20:23:01+00:00,7209075,pantsbuild/pants,1305167,cosmicexplorer,3065172,pantsbuild,opened,increase test coverage of the use of DependencyContext(),[],[],0,"In #5815 I discovered while debugging with @CMLivingston that when [`_closure_dep_predicate()` in `target.py`](https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/928be5de1e9350435f5c127d571584efba2dfb8f/src/python/pants/build_graph/target.py#L200) returns `None`, [`Target#strict_dependencies()` in the same file will try to invoke it as a callable](https://github.com/pantsbuild/pants/blob/928be5de1e9350435f5c127d571584efba2dfb8f/src/python/pants/build_graph/target.py#L651). There was a fix introduced in #5815 to handle this (using an always-true predicate if the result of `_closure_dep_predicate()` is `None`), but it's clear `strict_deps` and in particular the use of `DependencyContext` (which was expanded in #5815, but that didn't cause this error, nor did the zinc change right before -- this code path just wasn't being used) need some simple unit testing, either now, or as their use is expanded.",{},{}
11557,IssuesEvent,2017-12-20 21:45:13+00:00,82338450,ripple/dactyl,7515597,mDuo13,3165523,ripple,closed,Should report version number without reading config file,"[{'id': 542082323, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ripple/dactyl/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'ee0701', 'default': True}]",[],1,"if you're in a folder with a broken config file, or missing a custom filter, or something, `dactyl_build -v` errors out rather than doing what it's supposed to.

It shouldn't need to read the config file to output a version number.",{},{}
11610,IssuesEvent,2017-11-24 16:55:25+00:00,43388350,awslabs/aws-shell,4481827,mark-schaal,3299148,awslabs,opened,Feature: Local Endpoint Global Argument,[],[],0,"First, thanks for this utility! I noticed with `aws-shell` you can still pass in all the standard arguments for commands which includes endpoint mapping for local utility alternatives (e.g. dynamodb-local). After having used this tool frequently with some local development projects, I thought it might be useful to raise a feature request which would allow any service with local environment alternatives to be passed in via a global argument while instantiating `aws-shell`.

For example, if I am working with DynamoDB locally, I may want to use the following command to begin all interactions with a local endpoint:

`$ aws-shell --profile <PROFILE> --endpoint-url <http://localhost:8000>;`


",{},{}
