12353,IssuesEvent,2018-02-17 03:01:15+00:00,91020334,ni/nimi-python,8085768,marcoskirsch,5598284,ni,opened,datetime.timedelta not precise enough for all nimi-python use cases,"[{'id': 656403030, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ni/nimi-python/labels/API', 'name': 'API', 'color': 'fbca04', 'default': False}, {'id': 603245017, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ni/nimi-python/labels/enhancement', 'name': 'enhancement', 'color': '84b6eb', 'default': True}, {'id': 735743004, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/ni/nimi-python/labels/niscope', 'name': 'niscope', 'color': '3f5cc6', 'default': False}]",[],0,"#659 is merged which is great because it's slick. However, it introduced one problem: Python's built-in datetime.timedelta is not precise enough for all of nimi-python's use cases.

For example:
The NI-SCOPE attribute NISCOPE_ATTR_END_OF_RECORD_TO_ADVANCE_TRIGGER_HOLDOFF is specified as a ViReal64 (which is a double) in the C API and can have values with resolution greater than a microsecond.
But in the Python API this corresponds to [`niscope.Session.end_of_record_to_advance_trigger_holdoff`](http://nimi-python.readthedocs.io/en/master/niscope/attributes.html#niscope.Session.end_of_record_to_advance_trigger_holdoff) which is a [datetime.datetime](https://docs.python.org/2/library/datetime.html#timedelta-objects) and can only be specified in resolution of microseconds but not smaller.
",{},{}
