12887,IssuesEvent,2017-12-12 16:40:05+00:00,6235174,conda/conda,38393,msarahan,6392739,conda,opened,Need encoded package variant info in hash visible in conda list,[],[],0,"@jakirkham commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566)

Is `PKG_BUILD_STRING` defined during the Jinja pass of `meta.yaml`? If not, it would be really helpful in cases where a user might want to append to `conda-build`'s existing build string for a package.

---

@msarahan commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566#issuecomment-351078016)

This is a little bit nonsensical.  If it's defined during jinja2 passes (of which there are many), then it is ill-defined and appending to it will be painful.  Aside from this, if build/string is set, then conda-build's existing build string doesn't ever exist.  It is only a default value when build/string is not set, so the notion of building on it for a different build string won't work.

---

@jakirkham commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566#issuecomment-351081265)

Right, completely hear you. Not sure the right way to handle this. Was thinking about this in the context of appending to the build strings to making things like [variants]( https://gist.github.com/mcg1969/20667002c79f702e3c7003c81b5f24c8 ) a little nicer to handle without duplicating `conda-build`'s logic in Jinja in the `meta.yaml`. Any other suggestions on how to approach this problem?

---

@msarahan commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566#issuecomment-351085639)

I really don't think setting build strings for variants is the right way.  That is exactly what I was trying to avoid when I created the hashes.  I think letting the hash be the build string, and then letting conda sort out the underlying dependencies is a much better (if a bit more inscrutable) way.

---

@jakirkham commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566#issuecomment-351088209)

Honestly I'm not too attached to how the variant problem is solved, but am more concerned that `defaults` and `conda-forge` move towards solving it the same way.

Just so I understand what you're suggesting, we would still have a metapackage for selecting the variant and all things using this variant would require it. The packages requiring different variants would hash differently based on the variant selected (and other factors). Is that correct? Did I miss anything?

---

@msarahan commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566#issuecomment-351094572)

Yes, that's exactly correct.  The missing piece is how to make it ""nice"" to see which variant of a package is installed.  I believe we need to hack ``conda list`` or create an equivalent tool.  With packages produced by conda-build 3.1, their hash is composed entirely of variant info.  3.0-built packages have lots of other stuff that will need to be filtered.

---

@jakirkham commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566#issuecomment-351100712)

Ok, that sounds fine. Agreed we need to expose this when doing `conda list` (maybe even `conda env export`).

Guessing hashes are included in `conda env export` and `conda list`, correct?

---

@msarahan commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566#issuecomment-351105797)

Yeah, hashes are just part of the build string, so they're going to be wherever build strings always have been.

---

@jakirkham commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566#issuecomment-351108184)

Happy to have this closed or repurposed for the variant `conda list` problem.

---

@msarahan commented on [Tue Dec 12 2017](https://github.com/conda/conda-build/issues/2566#issuecomment-351108521)

Yes, I believe this is best repurposed into an issue about easy ways to see what variants of packages are present.  I'm going to change the title, then kick this over to the conda issue tracker.  I'll still assign it to myself, but having it there makes more sense.

",{},{}
