13082,IssuesEvent,2016-01-12 16:40:38+00:00,12235583,elastic/curator,3185476,panda87,6764390,elastic,closed,Run curator where the http enabled param is false,[],[],2,"Hi

I have a situation that I built new cluster with 3 data (master) nodes + 2 client nodes.
On the data nodes I set http.enabled to be false, so only the client nodes will receive external traffic.
Before I set the http.enabled to be false in the data nodes I used the --master only param and installed curator in all the data instances.

Now when I can't run the curator local on the data nodes since port 9200 is closed, where can I run the curator commands to avoid duplicates in the commands?

Thanks.
D.",{},{}
13090,IssuesEvent,2015-04-06 13:45:37+00:00,9801644,elastic/elasticsearch-py,32132,HonzaKral,6764390,elastic,closed,Memory leak in elasticsearch-py?,[],[],18,"I have created an index containing around 52,000 documents, each one containing data about a single person. I want to search for these persons by name. To see if my indexing- and searching-options are optimal, I devised a series of tests where I search for each person by name, and check which results I get back. These tests first used Mozilla's `elasticutils` library (which is built on top of `elasticsearch-py`). I found that the tests were using a lot of memory on the client side. Eventually the process started swapping, and I had to kill it. I replaced the `elasticutils` code with code that used `elasticsearch-py`, but I got the same memory problems. Finally I rewrote the tests so that they used the standard `httplib` and `json` libraries, and that seemed to solve the problem.

This table shows the memory usage (in kilobyte) for each version of my tests:

#searches | elasticutils | elasticsearch-py | httplib/json
--------------|--------------|------------------|-----------------
       0 |        37284 |         36548 |   36560
     500 |       316136 |        331344 |   37320
    1000 |       604160 |        631728 |   37336
    1500 |       880568 |        919912 |   37356
    2000 |      1163572 |       1223332 |   37356
    2500 |      1466908 |       1547208 |   37356
    3000 |      1773860 |       1863016 |   37356

This is the code I used to perform a search:

    from elasticsearch import Elasticsearch
    es = Elasticsearch([{""host"": ""localhost"", ""port"": 9200}])
    results = es.search(index=""myindex"", body={...}, size=100)

I'm using `elasticsearch` v1.4.0 and Python v2.7.5.

Is there any option I have overlooked that can solve the memory problem, or is there indeed a memory leak?",{},{}
