13695,IssuesEvent,2016-06-16 09:49:05+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,151929,minrk,7388996,jupyter,closed,Currently pip install --pre -e . ≠ pip3 install --pre -e .,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/jupyter/notebook/labels/needs-info', 'name': 'needs-info', 'color': 'ffffff'}]",[],6,"When I follow the instructions exactly for installing the dev master branch of the notebook 

    pip install --pre -e 

it builds `notebook-4.1.0.dev0`. 

However if I run what should be an equivalent command (just using `python3` and `pip3` instead):

    pip3 install --pre -e 

it builds the most recently released version of the notebook which at this time is `notebook-4.0.6`.

This seemed like an undesirable asymmetry for what should be equivalent commands, but it may be that there's something about `pip3` that I don't know. Otherwise, I figure it's a bug, and I don't know enough about `distutils` and the differences between `pip` and `pip3` to fix it myself. ",{},{}
13700,IssuesEvent,2017-08-20 16:33:50+00:00,33653601,jupyter/notebook,327925,takluyver,7388996,jupyter,closed,once-only events fired before custom.js is loaded,[],[],21,"Earlier in https://github.com/jupyter/notebook/issues/1730 we had an issue where the point at which `custom.js` was loaded was delayed so that standard triggers wouldn't work. It seems that with notebook 5.0 this bug was reintroduced.

This is a problem for scripts using `notebook_loaded.Notebook` as well as `app_initialized.NotebookApp` (likely the cause of https://github.com/jupyter/notebook/issues/2403). 

I don't know if https://github.com/jupyter/notebook/pull/1732 give an idea for a similar solution — but if it should be a Promise, my guess is it needs a slightly different kind of fix. Happy to attempt a fix if someone wants to point me in the right direction; seems like a good way to learn about Promises.",{},{}
