14502,IssuesEvent,2016-04-13 20:11:19+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,4974718,jaysee,9289019,letsencrypt,opened,"Install OK, but can't run letsencrypt if lsb_release is not installed",[],[],0,"Hi,

I was trying to install letsencrypt on my debian 7.10, installation was OK, but when launching lestencrypt --apache, I was having : 
```
./letsencrypt-auto --apache
Checking for new version...
Requesting root privileges to run letsencrypt...
   /root/.local/share/letsencrypt/bin/letsencrypt --apache
The apache plugin is not working; there may be problems with your existing configuration.
The error was: NotSupportedError('Apache plugin support requires libaugeas0 and augeas-lenses version 1.2.0 or higher, please make sure you have you have those installed.',)
```

After installing lsb_release (apt-get install lsb-release) and reinstalling letsencrypt, I now can run and install my certs.

perhaps on some OS, lsb_relase should be a dependency ?

Thank you for your work!",{},{}
14525,IssuesEvent,2015-11-04 23:38:05+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,1616242,kroeckx,9289019,letsencrypt,opened,Removes config file during renewal resulting in error,[],[],0,"I'm on a Debian system and I have the config files /etc/apache2/sites-available/  This is also where it's writing the new config file.  But to enable it I need to create a symlink in /etc/apache2/sites-enabled/.

It seems that somewhere during the renewal it removes the file in sites-available creating a dangling symlink which then results in an error trying to restart apache2, breaking the whole process.

I also don't think it's a good idea to remove that file in any case, it will cause the site to go down even if you remove the symlink too.  Also, since I had to edit the file because of other bugs I would appreciate that you didn't revert my changes. ",{},{}
