14577,IssuesEvent,2016-03-15 02:08:56+00:00,26516210,letsencrypt/letsencrypt,479213,pde,9289019,letsencrypt,closed,Why do we recommend --duplicate as a way of expanding a cert?,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/cert%20management', 'name': 'cert management', 'color': '00dece'}, {'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/labels/documentation', 'name': 'documentation', 'color': 'bfd4f2'}]",[],3,"In `cli.py` at line 363 we say

https://github.com/letsencrypt/letsencrypt/blob/master/letsencrypt/cli.py#L363

""--expand (or, in some cases, --duplicate)"".

These two options have opposite behaviors with respect to controlling the creation of new lineages. What are the ""some cases"" in which `--duplicate` would be appropriate to ""expand and replace th[e] existing certificate with the new certificate""? Could we remove the parenthesis there? I think it's even leading people astray to try `--duplicate` when it's not useful to them at all.",{},{}
