14609,IssuesEvent,2017-01-30 20:13:59+00:00,56217288,confluentinc/confluent-kafka-python,24443646,johnrgregg3,9439498,confluentinc,opened,What determines when Consumer.poll() returns?,[],[],0,"As I interpret the documentation at http://docs.confluent.io/3.1.1/clients/confluent-kafka-python/ , the parameter I give Consumer.poll() tells it to block for that amount of time (seconds? The document does not specify any units, it just says ""maximum time to wait"") if nothing interesting happens before the timeout. So I would imagine that when I call poll(2.0), if there was a message to receive, I would get that message immediately, but if not, I would block for 2 seconds. But it looks like I always return immediately, no matter what I give as a timeout to poll(), even when there are no messages or errors returned. Am I misinterpreting something?

I tried to understand the underlying rd_kafka_q_pop_serve(), but I'm not confident that I understand it. I wonder if my python callbacks (on_commit, on_assign, error_cb, stats_cb) should return a value, 0 or 1. Right now I just return, no value at all. The documentation does not mention any return value from the callbacks.

Thanks.",{},{}
14610,IssuesEvent,2017-03-02 21:54:44+00:00,56217288,confluentinc/confluent-kafka-python,524990,edenhill,9439498,confluentinc,closed,Under what conditions does Consumer.poll() return None?,"[{'id': 407409076, 'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/confluentinc/confluent-kafka-python/labels/librdkafka', 'name': 'librdkafka', 'color': 'f9d0c4', 'default': False}]",[],4,"The documentation for `Consumer.poll()` now indicates that `None` is a valid return value (I believe this  was changed at some point, see #18). I had been following the suggestion in #18 to just retry the `poll()` call if `None` was returned, but recently ran into a situation where that caused one of my applications to hang (I can't reproduce this, the kafka cluster was quite unhealthy when this happened). I would now like to be able to detect when the `None` return is signaling a transient system state that we expect to resolve itself and when it is an expected return.

It seems like once I get a `_PARTITION_EOF`, I will just get `None` after that until more data comes in. Is that correct? What are the other situations where I should expect `None` and which of them indicate some kind of bad system state that should resolve itself relatively quickly, and which are more ""normal"" conditions?

Thanks,
Aaron",{},{}
14624,IssuesEvent,2016-05-11 18:18:05+00:00,32411922,initios/flake8-junit-report,2385242,carlosgoce,9527795,initios,closed,Command line utility not working on Windows,"[{'url': 'https://api.github.com/repos/initios/flake8-junit-report/labels/bug', 'name': 'bug', 'color': 'fc2929'}]",[],6,"On Windows 10 using Python 3.5.1:

```bat
>pip -V
pip 8.0.2
>pip install flake8-junit-report
>pip list
...
flake8-junit-report (2.0.1)
...
>flake8_junit
'flake8_junit' is not recognized as an internal or external command,
operable program or batch file.
```

I think what you want is something like a `console_scripts` [`entry_point`](https://pythonhosted.org/setuptools/setuptools.html#new-and-changed-setup-keywords):
```python
setuptools.setup(
    ...
    entry_points={
            'console_scripts': [
                'flake8_junit = (INSERT MAIN MODULE):main',
            ],
```

This will work on Linux and Windows.",{},{}
