14985,IssuesEvent,2018-05-26 15:16:37+00:00,40094312,pyserial/pyserial,313511,wimg,10537924,pyserial,opened,pySerial read() dropping bytes (consistently),[],[],0,"I'm having a very odd problem whereby pyserial.read() drops a single byte somewhere in the middle, but only when specific data is read.

I'm communicating wit[h a Mutek MTK-571 card dispenser (https://www.mutek.com/card-dispsenser-machine-mtk-571/) over 9600BPS, no hardware control (only 3 serial wires). At some point I have to read the RFID card data from the device and I send a command to do that.
The device reply to pySerial is always correct, except in a few cases (around 1%), where a single byte is missing. The problem does not occur when I use the Mutek Windows-based software and it also doesn't occur when I use a PHP-based serial library on Linux.

The exact data being returned (in hex) is :
`F2000006503232323130039406F200000F5060303231304D000404A5114EA90803DB`
but pySerial reads it as :
`F2000006503232323130039406F200000F5060303231304D000404A54EA90803DB`

The (hex) byte '11' is missing from the return.
My code looks like this :
`status = ser.read(1)
addr = ser.read(1)
        lenh = ser.read(1)
        lenl = ser.read(1)
        pmt = ser.read(1)
        cmd = ser.read(1)
        pm = ser.read(1)
        st0 = ser.read(1)
        st1 = ser.read(1)
        st2 = ser.read(1)
        if ord(lenl) > 0:
            data = ser.read(ord(lenl) - 6)
        else:
            data = ''
        etxt = ser.read(1)
        bcc = ser.read(1)
`
The problem occurs on the line :
`data = ser.read(ord(lenl) - 6)`
meaning the data is missing somewhere in the middle of that read statement.

Initialization is done via :
`ser = serial.Serial(
    port=args.device,
    baudrate=9600,
    parity=serial.PARITY_NONE,
    stopbits=serial.STOPBITS_ONE,
    bytesize=serial.EIGHTBITS,
    xonxoff=True,
    rtscts=False,
    dsrdtr=False,
    timeout=1
)
ser.isOpen()
`

I've tried all variations of xonxoff, rtscts and dsrdtr (some of which won't even work because of the 3 wire connection).

I'm stumped, especially given the fact that on the same machine and operating system and the same connected device it works fine when using a PHP library.

BTW : we also have similar issues with 2 other serial devices.

Any idea what could be causing this ?",{},{}
