15056,IssuesEvent,2017-04-06 15:40:35+00:00,66389094,nexB/license-expression,675997,pombredanne,10789967,nexB,opened,Add replace method to LicenseExpression,[],[],0,"I would like to replace a expression and by another expression in a given expression.
The semantics should be the same as the `string.replace` [stdlib](https://docs.python.org/2.7/library/string.html?highlight=string%20replace#string.replace) function eg:
```
string.replace(s, old, new[, maxreplace])

    Return a copy of string s with all occurrences of substring old replaced by new. 
    If the optional argument maxreplace is given, the first maxreplace occurrences are replaced.
```
e.g. the function should apply to all exact sub expressions matching old in the expression tree and should not be recursive like in `string.replace`:
```
>>> 'foobarbar'.replace('foobar', 'foo')
'foobar'
```

The maxreplace is not needed.

",{},{}
15077,IssuesEvent,2016-08-03 10:19:49+00:00,584410,django-tastypie/django-tastypie,134373,SeanHayes,10821692,django-tastypie,closed,"""y-m-dTh:m:s"" isn't parseable anymore",[],[],4,"Hey guys,

This commit 8cc07f64 looks to improve the performance of how datetime fields are parsed but it introduced a new issue, example: {{2010-11-10T03:07:43}} isn't parseable anymore:
```
In [1]: from django.utils import datetime_safe
In [2]: value = ""2010-11-10T03:07:43""
In [3]: from tastypie.utils import make_aware
In [4]: year, month, day = value[:10].split('-')
In [5]: hour, minute, second = value[10:18].split(':')
In [6]: make_aware(datetime_safe.datetime(int(year), int(month), int(day), int(hour), int(minute), int(second)))
---------------------------------------------------------------------------
ValueError                                Traceback (most recent call last)
<ipython-input-6-3f6b5d00106f> in <module>()
----> 1 make_aware(datetime_safe.datetime(int(year), int(month), int(day), int(hour), int(minute), int(second)))
ValueError: invalid literal for int() with base 10: 'T03'
```
The docsting says that the code should handle this case while it's not the case actually https://github.com/django-tastypie/django-tastypie/blob/master/tastypie/fields.py#L384

Why there is no unit test covering this case ?

Cheers!",{},{}
