15258,IssuesEvent,2016-11-17 17:00:10+00:00,21987374,django-json-api/django-rest-framework-json-api,1641431,arielpontes,11215076,django-json-api,opened,Supposedly overridable methods are actually static,[],[],0,"According to the [API section](http://django-rest-framework-json-api.readthedocs.io/en/stable/api.html#rest-framework-json-api-renderers-jsonrenderer) of the documentation, ""The `JSONRenderer` exposes a number of methods that you may override if you need highly custom rendering control."" However, many of these methods are actually static and there are hardcoded calls to them in the code, making them unoverridable. For example:

```python
@staticmethod
def extract_relationships(fields, resource, resource_instance):
    # Avoid circular deps
    from rest_framework_json_api.relations import ResourceRelatedField
    # ...

@staticmethod
def build_json_resource_obj(fields, resource, resource_instance, resource_name):
    # ...
    relationships = JSONRenderer.extract_relationships(fields, resource, resource_instance)
```

Shouldn't these be classmethods instead?",{},{}
15269,IssuesEvent,2018-03-14 10:32:19+00:00,18302786,IDSIA/sacred,5921144,TomVeniat,11296960,IDSIA,opened,Empty dicts disappear from config ,[],[],0,"Hi,

When using empty dictionaries as values in named configs or config updates, the parameter will be removed from the final configuration. This issue is also present when using nested dicts.

Running the following snippet using `python test.py with config_a` or `python test.py  with config_a empty_dict={}` with the current master version both result in a 
`TypeError: main is missing value(s) for ['empty_dict', 'nested_empty_dict']`

```python
from sacred import Experiment

ex = Experiment('Test')

@ex.named_config
def config_a():
    full_dict = {'k': 'v'}
    empty_dict = {}
    nested_empty_dict = {'k1': {'k2': {}}}

@ex.automain
def main(full_dict, empty_dict, nested_empty_dict):
    pass
```

This error doesn't show up when using `@ex.config`.

I think configs, named configs and config update should all behave identically and allow empty dicts as values. 
The problem seems to come from [this](https://github.com/IDSIA/sacred/blob/674d0dff22bb70378201d837dc0dbc1d8600c9cf/sacred/utils.py#L160) line, which causes the function to never yield if the value is an empty dict. I can make a PR with a [fix](https://github.com/TomVeniat/sacred/commit/b13fc05b9fa94bf8628a77d53bb8bdba51542e84) if this solution is okay.

Thanks !",{},{}
15272,IssuesEvent,2018-04-27 13:48:56+00:00,18302786,IDSIA/sacred,4952605,wjaskowski,11296960,IDSIA,opened,Tensorboard integration without Tensorflow,[],[],0,"I am using [tensorboardX](https://github.com/lanpa/tensorboard-pytorch) to log to tensorboard. Basically, tt provides an API to create the tensorboard event files on which you can run tensorboard. Obviously, sacred does not recognise it so I cannot see it on sacredboard. Can I somehow manually write specific entries to info so that trick mimic the usage of ""the proper"" tensorboard with sacred?",{},{}
15281,IssuesEvent,2018-01-31 04:06:49+00:00,28774758,ets-labs/python-dependency-injector,2900574,vporton,11329744,ets-labs,opened,Overriding a factory argument,[],[],0,"As I understand, there is no yet the following feature (please add it):

If we add a keyword argument to a factory provider, the keyword should be passed to the constructor of the object (overriding the corresponding arguments passed to the `Factory()` constructor).

```
processes_factory = providers.Factory(Process, logger=default_logger_factory, db=db_factory)
```

Now we would be able to call `processes(logger=send_to_browser)`.

This is especially useful when one has many keyword arguments in `providers.Factory()` and want to change one or several of them without duplicating all unchanged arguments.

Note that for singletons this should throw an exception.

Note that I am a novice in python-dependency-injector. I do not warrant all this is right.",{},{}
15284,IssuesEvent,2018-01-14 07:08:38+00:00,28774758,ets-labs/python-dependency-injector,701191,asyncee,11329744,ets-labs,opened,Question on testing with python-dependency-injector,[],[],0,"Hello and thank you for such a great library.

I have a question regarding of how to test application, that uses python-dependency-injector library.

Lets take simple usecase:

```
class EmailSender:
    def send(self, email):
        pass

class SmtpEmailSender:
    # implementation with use of smpt library

class EchoingEmailSender:
    # logging / printing to stdout implementation

def notify_users(email_sender, email):
    email_sender.send(email)
```

In production i want to use SmtpEmailSender, but in tests only EchoingEmailSender.
I have configured a container which provides me with production-ready class of EmailSender and using it like:

```
Services.notify_users(email)
```
So, notify_users get production-ready dependency injected.

So the question is: how do i switch implementation in tests?
Surely i can override this specific dependency, and it will work okay, but what if i have 10 containers with different providers, that is used by application, should i override them in every test i write?
I think it can become an error-prone approach.

Thanks.",{},{}
