16942,IssuesEvent,2018-01-23 14:33:26+00:00,3277149,pyFFTW/pyFFTW,425560,dvolgyes,16965121,pyFFTW,opened,monkey patching issue,[],[],0,"I think the monkey patching example became a bit outdated.
I mean it works well, except the speedup.
I think the reason is this:
scipy.signal.fftconvolve() is used in the example, but the inner part of fftconvolve
has changed, and now it uses rfftn and irfftn from scipy.fft_pack.
However, these two are not implemented in the pyFFTW interface.
(fftn and ifftn are implemented, also rfft and irfft, but not the rfftn and the irfftn.)

Due to the lack of implementation, I assume the code falls back to the scipy
version, and therefore there is no speedup.

I would recommend to implement these two missing interfaces,
or to change the monkey patching example.
",{},{}
16943,IssuesEvent,2016-01-29 22:35:02+00:00,3277149,pyFFTW/pyFFTW,701883,hgomersall,16965121,pyFFTW,closed,setup: some targets should not require numpy to be installed,[],[],2,"Targets like help or clean should not require numpy to be installed in order to execute. Again, this bug is to ease the packaging work where the clean command is usually executed before dependency resolution. 

The solution provided by scipy seems to be the widely accepted one, where the common metadata of the package are set first and the extension modules and package metadata are added if numpy is detected. Again, please have a look at my updated version of pyNFFT for a concrete example.",{},{}
