17272,IssuesEvent,2016-09-15 18:08:23+00:00,52238733,pyta-uoft/pyta,3333115,david-yz-liu,18420574,pyta-uoft,closed,Investigating type inference,[],"[{'login': 'hayleyZHL', 'id': 9983162, 'avatar_url': 'https://avatars.githubusercontent.com/u/9983162?v=3', 'gravatar_id': '', 'url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL', 'html_url': 'https://github.com/hayleyZHL', 'followers_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL/followers', 'following_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL/following{/other_user}', 'gists_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL/gists{/gist_id}', 'starred_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL/starred{/owner}{/repo}', 'subscriptions_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL/subscriptions', 'organizations_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL/orgs', 'repos_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL/repos', 'events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL/events{/privacy}', 'received_events_url': 'https://api.github.com/users/hayleyZHL/received_events', 'type': 'User', 'site_admin': False}]",0,"This is mainly an investigation issue (for now).

pylint already does some typechecking, but it doesn't do true type inference; it can't detect an error in something like:

```python
def f(x):
    a = x + 3
    b = x[0]   # this can't work if x + 3 does
    return a + b
```

And yet it *does* have a type checker: https://github.com/PyCQA/pylint/blob/master/pylint/checkers/typecheck.py

Pick a particular checker in there (like `no-member`), and figure out how it works. I looked into it briefly, and it seems this will require understanding what the `infer` method does (astroid provides). Not too much documentation, so looking through the source code will be important.

Also play around with the code itself: you should be able to define your own checker based on the typechecker, and simplify and modify the code to see how it works.",{},{}
